0,"steps":[{"id":1066185,"guid":"5222C9601A4111EBB336110A599A97AA","previous_id":null,"previous_guid":null,"modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"CDEC4411DB344F3B96A37E271BA64410","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"C78D572483EF48C4A13D194C99069A94","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">ARP is a weekly exercise and occupational therapy that facilitated participation with low (<3 MET) aerobic physical activity and, if possible, moderate (3 to 6 MET) physical activity. The participants collaborated on solving multiple tasks. To facilitate communication with local residents, the trial is carried out outside of the facility.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">In the first week, participants visit a shopping street to purchase the items for park cleaning and gardening. The total duration of transportation and shopping is approximately three hours. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">In weeks two to four, participants go to a nearby park for cleaning and gardening with or without walking aids. For cleaning, participants hold a pair of tongs or a bin liner and walk around in the park to pick up litters. For gardening, they dig the ground, plant flowers and water them. The supervised intervention is carried out once a week, but the participants are encouraged to visit the park to take care of the flowers on other days. This four-week series is repeated three times.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">The frequency, intensity, type and time of physical activities are summarized in Table 1.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Table 1. The basic components of Adachi Rehabilitation Programme<\/div><table border><tr style = \"text-align:center;\"><td>  <\/td><td>A<\/td><td>B<\/td><td>C<\/td><td>D<\/td><\/tr><tr><td style = \"text-align:center;\">1<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;